\begin_layout Subsection*
\noindent
Problem definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combined in diverse cellular assemblies that vary with cell cycle, tissue
 type and in response to external stimuli, proteins constitute the nanomachines
 of biology.
 Biological processes are governed by the well-defined organization of proteins
 into complexes, and understanding the principles regulating protein interaction
s remains an important endeavor.
 Major biological processes such as immunity, metabolism, signaling, gene
 expression, as well as the building of supramolecular assemblies and molecular
 machines are mediated through protein interactions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Substantial advances in experimental key technologies, including super-resolutio
n microscopy localization techniques, multi-color single molecule FRET spectrosc
opy, and cryo-electron microscopy, are offering an unprecedented view into
 the spatial and temporal organization of proteins and larger macromolecular
 complexes in the cellular environment.
 This is generating new insights and prompting more challenging questions
 on the physico/chemical principles underlying complex biological mechanisms.
 However, experiments are still lacking the ability to simultaneously resolve
 structure and dynamics in a way that would permit a full characterization
 of the assembly and dynamical mechanisms of large and partly unstructured
 proteins.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Computer simulations present an attractive complement to experiment.
 Recent advances in theoretical modeling and high-performance computing
 allow to simulate the molecular dynamics (MD) of protein systems at atomic-leve
l detail up to a few 100 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

s timescale on state-of-the-art computational resources.
 However, the time- and length-scales required to study the dynamic interplay
 of protein complexes and their interaction partners in complex biological
 mechanisms, let alone the efficiency required to explore many mutants and
 their phenotypes, still go far beyond atomistic MD.
 Recently proposed cellular dynamics simulations address the spatiotemporal
 reaction kinetics over significantly longer timescale and larger length-scale.
 However, in this approach intramolecular resolution is lost: a macromolecule
 is often represented as a few connected particles, precluding for instance
 the direct observation of structural dynamics within a protein, or the
 modeling of intrinsically disordered proteins.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We propose a modeling and computational approach for the characterization
 of protein interaction and assembly, at a scale that can bridge molecular
 and cellular studies.
 The simulation method we propose is computationally efficient due to a
 coarser-than-atomistic resolution, yet accurate by virtue of being optimized
 to obey experimentally reproduce thermodynamic and kinetic measurements.
 This approach will enable us to characterize the dynamics, assembly, and
 function of large biological complexes, involving intrinsically disordered
 proteins, large structural transitions, and metastable assemblies.
\end_layout

