\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
In the past few decades the study of collective/organizing motions at long
 timescales and system sizes inaccessible to atomistic simulations has been
 mostly based on coarse-grained models that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

renormalize
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 groups of atoms into 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

effective
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom.
 By sacrificing the atomistic details coarse-grained models can explore
 larger time and length scales, providing a good starting point to identify
 relevant regions on the vast configurational landscape of protein complexes.
 However, these simplified models are built with approximations and assumptions
 that may strongly affect the accuracy of the results.
 In order to fully exploit the advantages of a coarse-grained protein model
 without compromising the validity of the simulation, we have proposed an
 “inverse statistical mechanics” procedure for molecular modeling where
 experimentally measured quantities are the starting point for the definition
 of a model, as opposed to the “direct” approach where models can be used
 to obtain averages to be compared to experimental data.
 The idea is illustrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Scheme"

\end_inset

.
 In short, this procedure allows to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

anchor
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a model to available experimental data: it uses experimental data directly
 to determine the effective parameters of a molecular model, providing a
 way to test the assumptions lying at the base of the model and to characterize
 states of the system that may be inaccessible to experiments.
 The power of this method has been illustrated for instance on the study
 of the aggregation of a mutated form of protein S6.
 It was shown that the mutation of a specific set of residues triggers significa
nt changes on the configurational landscape of this protein.
 This study has provided clues on the mechanism adopted by the wild-type
 form of protein S6 to avoid aggregation, and supports the previously proposed
 hypothesis that a non-optimal twist between 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-strands may be a result of natural evolution to avoid edge-to-edge aggregation
 between several copies of the same protein.
 Ongoing work shows that complex experimental observables, such as FRET
 distributions can also be included in the method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Bayesian approach to optimal combination of experiment and simulation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The original formulation of our inverse method involved the application
 of free energy perturbation theory and a first order Taylor expansion in
 the parameter space of the selected model's Hamiltonian.
 We now plan to extend this method by using a Bayesian approach to measure
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

goodness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

, of the model Hamiltonian in reproducing a set of experimental observables
 (with associated uncertainties), then iteratively change the Hamiltonian
 to maximize 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 This approach has two significant advantages: (i) it naturally allows to
 combine together heterogenous experimental data (e.g., different sets of
 observables obtained from different experimental methods), and (ii) it
 associates an uncertainty to the model predictions.
 We are working on a rigorous Bayesian formulation that takes into account
 the statistical uncertainties of both experiment and simulation and can
 sample different solutions rather than returning one realization of the
 model.
 Here we present a simplified version that makes use of a maximum likelihood
 criterion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approach we propose starts with the definition of a family of models,
 with a large set of free parameters.
 In practice, this is done by assuming a geometric representation for the
 system, and a Hamiltonian function for the interaction energy among the
 system components.
 For instance, plausible choices may be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

-only or 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\alpha}-C_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 representation for proteins, and pairwise interaction potentials composed
 by a short-range repulsive core and as sum of multiple Gaussian functions
 centered at different positions.
 The relative weights of the Gaussians, as well as the associated means
 and variances can all be left as free parameters.
 We indicate the parameter set as 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that experimental measurements for the system of interest are available
 for a set of observables (e.g.
 binding energies, stability upon folding, expectation of some spectroscopic
 quantity).
 Each quantity is affiliated with an uncertainty.
 We denote the measured values and uncertainties as 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},\,...,\,f_{K})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Delta f_{1},\,...,\,\Delta f_{K})$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 For simplicity, we treat the measurements as independent and identically
 distributed, with a Normal error model
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It's straightforward to extend this error model if more information is available.
 For instance, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},\,...,\,f_{K})$
\end_inset

 are different frequencies or time-points of a nontrivial spectroscopic
 measurement, such as a spectrum, the different values are likely cross-correlat
ed.
 In this case the error model can be made more complex by using a multivariate
 Gaussian with a non-diagonal covariance matrix.
 If the functional form of the error is known, it can be used to replace
 the Gaussian model by a function that represents the specifics of experimental
 error.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 With this assumption, the likelihood of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true values
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the measured quantities being 
\begin_inset Formula $(e_{1},\,...,\,e_{K})$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left[(e_{1},\,...,\,e_{K})\mid\mathrm{Exp}\right]=\prod_{k}\mathcal{N}(e_{k};\:f_{k},\Delta f_{k})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}(x;\:\mu,\,\sigma)\propto\exp\left(-\frac{(x-\mu)^{2}}{2\sigma^{2}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the Gaussian density in variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to find the optimal values of the model parameters given the experimenta
l data, and a quantitative estimate of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

goodness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the model in reproducing the data.
 We are developing a propose to tackle this problem with the following iterative
 approach:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We use an initial ansatz for the parameter values, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We indicate the corresponding model Hamiltonian as 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 indicates a configuration of the system (e.g., the Cartesian coordinates
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 atoms of the protein(s)).
 We run molecular dynamics simulations with 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Based on the simulation data and a suitable analysis model, we can compute
 the conditional probability (
\shape italic
posterior
\shape default
) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left[\pi^{0}(\mathbf{x})\mid\mathrm{Sim},\,\epsilon_{0}\right]$
\end_inset

 for the equilibrium distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{0}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 given the model parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Computationally, the equilibrium distribution is usually evaluated on bins
 or discrete states, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 is not a function but a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\pi}$
\end_inset

.
 In practice, this distribution can be efficiently evaluated by discretizing
 the state space into 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 clusters, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,N$
\end_inset

 and build a Markov State Model (MSM) on it.
 Transitions between clusters are counted to define the count matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{ij}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the number of conditionally independent transition counts from 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The posterior for a MSM with transition matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left[\mathbf{P}\mid\mathrm{Sim}\,\epsilon_{0}\right]=\prod_{i}p_{ij}^{c_{ij}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ij}$
\end_inset

 are the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}$
\end_inset

.
 The maximum likelihood equilibrium distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\pi}$
\end_inset

 for such a model can be straightforwardly obtained by using available algorithm
s.
 Alternatively, we could simply discretize the state space into 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 bins 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,N$
\end_inset

 (for example, by using properly defined collective variables) and bin the
 data.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i}$
\end_inset

 the number of bin counts in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th bin, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The posterior is given by the multinomial distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left[\boldsymbol{\pi}\mid\mathrm{Sim,}\,\epsilon_{0}\right]=\prod_{i}\pi_{i}^{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

 with a maximum likelihood distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{i}=n_{i}/N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The simulation data are used to estimate the values of the observables for
 which we have the experimental measurements.
 We assume here that the measurement 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{k}$
\end_inset

 is an expectation value, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{k}=\int_{\mathbf{x}}\mu(\mathbf{x})\,g_{k}(\mathbf{x})\,\mathrm{d}\mathbf{x}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 is the Boltzmann density and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the function that computes the value of the experimental observable
 (e.g.
 a fluorescence) associated to a configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

.
 In practice, the expectation value is computed over the simulation equilibrium
 vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\pi}$
\end_inset

.
 The Boltzmann weight associated with a specific configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 in state 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 (cluster or bin) is then estimated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mu}(\mathbf{x})=\frac{\pi_{i}}{n_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and the predicted experimental value is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{e}_{k}[\boldsymbol{\pi}]=\sum_{i}\pi_{i}\frac{1}{n_{i}}\sum_{j\in S_{i}}g_{k}(\mathbf{x}_{ij})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th sampled configuration in discrete state 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

goodness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the parameters set 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{0}$
\end_inset

 can be quantified by evaluating the simulation prediction in the light
 of the experimental density :
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q^{0}=\mathbb{P}\left[(\tilde{e}_{1}[\boldsymbol{\pi^{0}}],\,...,\,\tilde{e}_{K}[\boldsymbol{\pi^{0}}])\mid\mathrm{Exp}\right]=\prod_{k}\mathcal{N}(\tilde{e}_{k};\:f_{k},\Delta f_{k})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
It is easy to show that the equilibrium distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\pi^{1}}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

 associated with a new parameter set 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

 obtained upon an infinitesimal change of the original values, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{1}=\epsilon_{0}+\delta\epsilon$
\end_inset

 (changing the model Hamiltonian from 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}(x)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}(x)$
\end_inset

), can be estimated by reweighing as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{i}^{1}=\frac{\pi_{i}^{0}}{n_{i}}\sum_{x\in S_{i}}\exp\left[-\beta(H_{0}(\mathbf{x})-H_{1}(\mathbf{x}))\right].
\]

\end_inset

With this reweighing an expression for the goodness function 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}^{1}=\mathbb{P}\left[(\tilde{e}_{1}[\boldsymbol{\pi^{1}}],\,...,\,\tilde{e}_{K}[\boldsymbol{\pi^{1}}])\mid\mathrm{Exp}\right]$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

 can be obtained.
 We then make a step in the parameter space in the direction that maximizes
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 New simulations are run with the new parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{1}$
\end_inset

 , a new posterior 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}\left[\pi^{1}(\mathbf{x})\mid\mathrm{Sim},\,\epsilon_{1}\right]$
\end_inset

 is obtained, and the steps above are repeated until convergence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
\noindent

\series bold
Scientific relevance and broader impact
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Thanks to the technological and methodological advances of the last few
 decades, we now know many key molecular players in many fundamental biological
 processes.
 However, a comprehensive view of these processes is still lacking.
 Oftentimes, an abundance of structural, thermodynamical, or kinetic measurement
s is available at least for parts of the components in the system of interest.
 The structural information 
\emph on
per se
\emph default
 is incomplete as the macromolecules involved are often partly disordered
 and/or need to change configurations to perform their functions.
 A theoretical/modeling framework able to integrate all the available (pieces
 of) information for a given cellular process over a multiple range of time-
 and length-scales is essential to obtain a global and quantitative understandin
g of the process, but it is at present not available.
 The proposed project will contribute to create such a modeling approach.
 We believe it will be able to explain how the different molecular components
 organize and interact as a function of time and space in performing a cellular
 function.
 
\end_layout

